    title: "Frames of Reference in OT",
    cellular: "Frames of reference provide theoretical foundations for evaluation and intervention. Biomechanical: focuses on strength, range of motion, and endurance for musculoskeletal conditions. Rehabilitative/compensatory: uses adaptive strategies and assistive devices to promote independence despite impairment. Motor control/motor learning: emphasizes task-oriented practice and neural plasticity. Sensory integration: addresses sensory processing and modulation for functional performance. Cognitive: uses cognitive strategies, environmental modification, and skill training. MOHO (Model of Human Occupation): examines volition, habituation, and performance capacity. PEO (Person-Environment-Occupation): analyzes the fit between person, environment, and occupation. Frame selection is guided by client needs, diagnosis, and treatment setting.",
