    cellular: "Activities of daily living (ADLs) include bathing, dressing, eating, functional mobility, personal hygiene, toileting, and sexual activity. ADL assessment uses standardized tools: Barthel Index, FIM (Functional Independence Measure), Katz Index of Independence, and performance-based observation. Assessment identifies what the client can do independently, what requires assistance, and what is not possible. Intervention approaches: remediation (improving underlying skills), compensation (adaptive techniques and equipment), and environmental modification. Common adaptive equipment: long-handled reacher, sock aid, button hook, built-up utensils, tub bench, raised toilet seat, and grab bars. Grading dressing activities from simple to complex builds competence progressively.",
